{
  "steps": [
    {
      "text": "Go to https://git-scm.com/downloads in your web browser. You'll see download options for Windows, Mac, and Linux. The site usually detects your OS automatically and highlights the recommended version.",
      "title": "Open the Git Downloads Page"
    },
    {
      "text": "Click the download button for your operating system. For Windows, this downloads an .exe installer. For Mac, you may see several options — choose the one labeled \"homebrew\" if you have it, or \"installer\" otherwise.",
      "title": "Download the Installer"
    },
    {
      "text": "On Mac with Homebrew, open Terminal and type `brew install git`, then press Enter. Skip to the verification step once it finishes. On Linux (Debian/Ubuntu), open a terminal and type `sudo apt install git`, then press Enter.",
      "title": "Install via Package Manager (Mac/Linux)"
    },
    {
      "text": "On Windows, locate the downloaded .exe file in your Downloads folder and double-click it. A setup wizard will open. If Windows asks for permission to run the file, click Yes.",
      "title": "Run the Windows Installer"
    },
    {
      "text": "Click Next through the installer screens to accept the default options. These defaults work well for most users. When you reach the \"Adjusting your PATH environment\" screen, keep the recommended middle option selected.",
      "title": "Accept the Default Settings"
    },
    {
      "text": "Click Install on the final confirmation screen. A progress bar will appear. Wait for it to complete — this usually takes less than a minute. Once finished, click Finish to close the wizard.",
      "title": "Complete the Installation"
    },
    {
      "text": "Open Terminal (Mac/Linux) or Git Bash (Windows — search for it in the Start menu). Type `git --version` and press Enter. You should see output like \"git version 2.x.x\". This confirms Git installed successfully.",
      "title": "Verify the Installation"
    },
    {
      "text": "If you see \"command not found\" instead of a version number, restart your terminal and try again. On Windows, make sure you're using Git Bash, not the regular Command Prompt. If the issue persists, re-run the installer and try again.",
      "title": "Troubleshoot If Needed"
    }
  ]
}

{
  "steps": [
    {
      "text": "Before jacking the car, use the lug wrench to loosen each lug nut on the flat tire by turning counterclockwise. Don't remove them yet — just break the resistance. The tire should stay still while you turn.",
      "title": "Loosen the Lug Nuts First"
    },
    {
      "text": "Check your owner's manual or look for a small arrow or notch stamped on the door frame to find the correct jack point near the flat tire. Using the wrong spot can damage your car or cause the jack to slip.",
      "title": "Find the Jack Point"
    },
    {
      "text": "Slide the jack under the vehicle at the marked jack point. Make sure the jack head connects with the vehicle's metal frame, not plastic trim. A misaligned jack can bend body panels or fail under load.",
      "title": "Position the Jack"
    },
    {
      "text": "Turn the jack handle clockwise to slowly raise the vehicle. Stop when the flat tire is about 6 inches off the ground. Check that the car feels stable — it should not wobble or shift as you lift.",
      "title": "Raise the Vehicle"
    },
    {
      "text": "Now fully remove each lug nut by hand, turning counterclockwise. Place them together in a safe spot like your pocket or a cup holder so none roll away. You'll need all of them for the spare.",
      "title": "Remove the Lug Nuts"
    },
    {
      "text": "Grip the flat tire at the 3 and 9 o'clock positions and pull it straight toward you. It may feel stiff — wiggle gently if needed. Set it flat on the ground away from the vehicle and traffic.",
      "title": "Pull Off the Flat Tire"
    },
    {
      "text": "Look at the hub where the tire was mounted. If you see any visible damage, cracks, or brake dust buildup, wipe the surface with a clean rag before mounting the spare.",
      "title": "Inspect the Wheel Hub"
    }
  ]
}

{
  "steps": [
    {
      "text": "You'll need a French press, coarsely ground coffee (2 tablespoons per 6 oz of water), a kettle, a timer, and your mug. Everything should be within arm's reach before you start.",
      "title": "Gather Your Equipment"
    },
    {
      "text": "Pour hot water into your empty French press and swirl it around for 10 seconds, then discard it. This warms the glass and helps maintain brewing temperature throughout the process.",
      "title": "Preheat the French Press"
    },
    {
      "text": "Add your coarsely ground coffee to the empty French press. For a standard 8-cup press, use about 8 tablespoons (56g) of grounds. The texture should resemble coarse sea salt.",
      "title": "Add the Coffee Grounds"
    },
    {
      "text": "Heat your water to 200°F (93°C). If you don't have a thermometer, bring water to a full boil, then let it sit for 30 seconds. You should see steam rising but no active bubbling.",
      "title": "Heat the Water"
    },
    {
      "text": "Start your timer and pour just enough hot water to saturate all the grounds — about twice the weight of the coffee. Pour slowly in a circular motion. You should see the grounds bubble and rise slightly.",
      "title": "Pour Water to Bloom"
    },
    {
      "text": "Wait 30 seconds for the bloom. This releases trapped CO₂ from the grounds. You'll see the coffee puff up, then settle. This step ensures even extraction and better flavor.",
      "title": "Wait for the Bloom"
    },
    {
      "text": "Pour the remaining hot water slowly in a circular motion until you reach the desired level, leaving about half an inch of space at the top. Place the lid on the press with the plunger pulled all the way up.",
      "title": "Add the Rest of the Water"
    },
    {
      "text": "Set your timer for 4 minutes and don't touch the press. This is the full extraction time. The lid traps heat while the grounds steep. You should see a dark layer forming at the top.",
      "title": "Start the 4-Minute Timer"
    },
    {
      "text": "When the timer goes off, grip the handle firmly and press the plunger straight down with steady, slow pressure. It should take about 20–30 seconds. If it feels too easy, your grind is too coarse.",
      "title": "Press the Plunger Down"
    },
    {
      "text": "Pour the coffee into your mug immediately after plunging. Don't let it sit in the French press — the grounds will keep extracting and the coffee will turn bitter within minutes.",
      "title": "Pour Into Your Mug"
    },
    {
      "text": "Your cup should be rich, deep brown with a smooth, full-bodied texture. If it tastes too bitter, coarsen your grind next time. If it tastes weak or sour, use a finer grind or extend brew time by 30 seconds.",
      "title": "Check the Results"
    }
  ]
}

{
  "steps": [
    {
      "text": "Gather a garden fork or spade, compost or aged manure, a pH testing kit, and garden lime or sulfur. Having everything on hand before you start will make the process smooth and uninterrupted.",
      "title": "Gather Your Tools and Amendments"
    },
    {
      "text": "Walk to your chosen garden bed and clear away any weeds, rocks, or debris by hand or with a hoe. A clean surface makes it easier to work the soil evenly.",
      "title": "Clear the Garden Bed"
    },
    {
      "text": "Insert your garden fork or spade 10–12 inches into the soil and turn it over in sections. Work across the entire bed systematically. The soil should break apart and crumble — if it clumps heavily, it may need more moisture before continuing.",
      "title": "Loosen the Soil"
    },
    {
      "text": "Use your pH testing kit on a small soil sample following the kit's instructions. Tomatoes thrive at a pH of 6.0–6.8. Note your reading so you know whether to add lime (too acidic) or sulfur (too alkaline).",
      "title": "Test the Soil pH"
    },
    {
      "text": "If your pH reading was below 6.0, sprinkle garden lime evenly across the bed per the package rate. If it was above 6.8, apply sulfur instead. Skip this step if your reading was already within range.",
      "title": "Adjust the pH if Needed"
    },
    {
      "text": "Spread a 2–3 inch layer of compost or aged manure evenly across the surface of the loosened bed. You should see a uniform dark layer covering the entire area before mixing it in.",
      "title": "Add Compost or Manure"
    },
    {
      "text": "Use your fork or spade to work the compost down into the top 8–10 inches of soil. Mix thoroughly until no large pockets of compost remain visible and the amendment is evenly blended throughout.",
      "title": "Work the Amendment Into the Soil"
    },
    {
      "text": "Use a garden rake to level the bed surface by pushing and pulling it in long, even strokes. The finished surface should be flat and roughly smooth with no large clumps or low spots.",
      "title": "Rake the Surface Smooth"
    },
    {
      "text": "Press a small handful of soil firmly in your fist, then open your hand and poke it with a finger. If it crumbles apart, the texture is ready. If it stays in a wet ball, let the bed dry out for a day before planting.",
      "title": "Check Soil Consistency"
    },
    {
      "text": "Water the prepared bed gently using a watering can or hose with a gentle spray setting until the top 6 inches are moist but not waterlogged. The soil is now conditioned and ready for tomato planting.",
      "title": "Moisten the Prepared Bed"
    }
  ]
}

{
  "steps": [
    {
      "text": "Gather your fabric (at least 1 yard of cotton), a ruler or measuring tape, fabric marker or chalk, scissors or rotary cutter, cutting mat, and straight pins. Wash and iron your fabric before cutting to prevent shrinking later.",
      "title": "Gather Your Supplies"
    },
    {
      "text": "Lay your fabric flat on your cutting mat or table with the right side facing down. Smooth out any wrinkles with your hands or re-iron if needed. Wrinkled fabric leads to inaccurate cuts.",
      "title": "Lay Out the Fabric"
    },
    {
      "text": "Using your ruler and fabric marker, measure and mark a rectangle 27\" x 21\" on your fabric. This is the main body piece. Double-check your measurements before marking — measure twice, cut once.",
      "title": "Mark the Main Body Piece"
    },
    {
      "text": "Measure and mark a second rectangle 27\" x 9\" on your fabric. This is the cuff piece that will form the decorative fold-over edge at the opening of the pillowcase.",
      "title": "Mark the Cuff Piece"
    },
    {
      "text": "Place straight pins along the inside of each marked rectangle, about 1\" from the lines. Pins should be perpendicular to the lines. This holds the fabric layers in place if your fabric has shifted or has multiple layers.",
      "title": "Pin Along the Marked Lines"
    },
    {
      "text": "Using sharp fabric scissors, cut along the marked lines of the main body piece with long, smooth strokes. Avoid short choppy cuts — they create jagged edges. Keep the fabric flat as you cut.",
      "title": "Cut the Main Body Piece"
    },
    {
      "text": "Cut along the marked lines of the cuff piece the same way. Use long, smooth strokes and keep scissors parallel to the cutting surface for a clean, straight edge.",
      "title": "Cut the Cuff Piece"
    },
    {
      "text": "Hold each cut piece up and measure it with your ruler. The main body should be 27\" x 21\" and the cuff should be 27\" x 9\". If a piece is off by more than ¼\", trim or re-cut before moving on.",
      "title": "Check Your Measurements"
    },
    {
      "text": "Remove all pins from both pieces. Stack the pieces neatly and set aside in a safe spot. Your fabric is now ready for the next stage: sewing the pillowcase together.",
      "title": "Remove Pins and Set Aside"
    }
  ]
}

{
  "steps": [
    {
      "text": "Download a free tuner app such as GuitarTuna or Fender Tune from your phone's app store, or clip a physical chromatic tuner onto your guitar's headstock. Have it open and ready before you begin.",
      "title": "Get a tuner ready"
    },
    {
      "text": "Hold your guitar in playing position — either seated with the body resting on your leg or standing with a strap. Keep the headstock (where the tuning pegs are) angled slightly upward so you can reach the pegs easily.",
      "title": "Hold your guitar properly"
    },
    {
      "text": "Pluck the thickest string — the low E string. This is the string closest to the ceiling when holding the guitar. Pluck it firmly with your thumb or a pick so the tuner can detect the note.",
      "title": "Play the 6th string (low E)"
    },
    {
      "text": "Watch your tuner's display. It will show which note it detects. If the needle or bar is to the left, the string is flat (too low). If it's to the right, it's sharp (too high). You want the indicator centered on E.",
      "title": "Read the tuner display"
    },
    {
      "text": "Turn the tuning peg for the low E string slowly. Turning it away from you usually raises the pitch; toward you lowers it. Make small adjustments and repluck the string after each turn to recheck the reading.",
      "title": "Adjust the tuning peg"
    },
    {
      "text": "Keep adjusting and replucking until the tuner shows E with the indicator centered and the display turns green (or shows a checkmark). The low E string is now in tune.",
      "title": "Confirm the low E is in tune"
    },
    {
      "text": "Move to the 5th string (A). Pluck it and check the tuner. It should read A. Adjust the corresponding tuning peg until the indicator centers on A and the tuner confirms it's in tune.",
      "title": "Tune the 5th string (A)"
    },
    {
      "text": "Pluck the 4th string (D). The tuner should detect D. Adjust the peg until the indicator is centered and the tuner confirms the note. Small turns go a long way — move slowly.",
      "title": "Tune the 4th string (D)"
    },
    {
      "text": "Pluck the 3rd string (G). Adjust its tuning peg until the tuner reads G with the indicator centered. This string can slip easily, so confirm it a second time by replucking after you've centered it.",
      "title": "Tune the 3rd string (G)"
    },
    {
      "text": "Pluck the 2nd string (B). Adjust the peg until the tuner reads B with the indicator centered. If the string feels very loose or very tight, double-check you're turning the correct peg — each peg corresponds to one string only.",
      "title": "Tune the 2nd string (B)"
    },
    {
      "text": "Pluck the 1st string — the thinnest one, closest to the floor. Adjust its peg until the tuner reads E and the indicator centers. This is the high E, which is two octaves above the low E string.",
      "title": "Tune the 1st string (high E)"
    },
    {
      "text": "Go back to the low E string and pluck all six strings again one by one. Tuning one string can slightly affect the tension of others. Make small corrections if any string has drifted off center.",
      "title": "Do a final check on all strings"
    },
    {
      "text": "Strum all six strings together slowly. The sound should feel full and balanced, not jarring or off. If something sounds wrong, use the tuner to identify and correct the problematic string.",
      "title": "Strum to confirm tuning"
    }
  ]
}

{
  "steps": [
    {
      "text": "Set your camera to Manual (M) mode using the mode dial on top of the camera. You should see \"M\" displayed on your camera's LCD screen or viewfinder.",
      "title": "Switch to Manual Mode"
    },
    {
      "text": "Look at your camera's built-in light meter, usually displayed as a scale at the bottom of the viewfinder. Aim for the indicator to sit at the center (0) for correct exposure.",
      "title": "Read the Light Meter"
    },
    {
      "text": "Press the ISO button (or go to Menu > ISO Settings) and set ISO to 100 for bright daylight, 400 for cloudy/shade, or 800–3200 for indoors or low light.",
      "title": "Set Your ISO"
    },
    {
      "text": "Rotate the aperture dial (or rear command dial) to choose your f-stop. Use f/1.8–f/4 for blurry backgrounds, f/8–f/11 for sharp landscapes. Your viewfinder will show the f-number change.",
      "title": "Choose Your Aperture"
    },
    {
      "text": "Rotate the shutter speed dial (or front command dial) to select your speed. Use 1/500s or faster for moving subjects, 1/60s–1/125s for still scenes. The viewfinder displays the current value.",
      "title": "Set Your Shutter Speed"
    },
    {
      "text": "Check your light meter again after setting all three values. If the indicator is to the left (–), increase ISO or widen aperture. If it's to the right (+), decrease ISO or narrow aperture.",
      "title": "Check the Exposure Balance"
    },
    {
      "text": "Half-press the shutter button to let the camera meter the scene. Confirm the light meter indicator sits at or near center (0) before taking your shot.",
      "title": "Verify Exposure Before Shooting"
    },
    {
      "text": "Press the shutter button fully to take the photo. Review the image on your LCD screen immediately after.",
      "title": "Take the Shot"
    },
    {
      "text": "Inspect the image on the LCD. If it looks too bright (overexposed), increase shutter speed or narrow aperture. If too dark (underexposed), slow the shutter or widen aperture, then reshoot.",
      "title": "Review and Fine-Tune"
    },
    {
      "text": "Enable the histogram display (Menu > Playback > Histogram) to see an accurate exposure graph. A good exposure shows a bell-shaped curve with no clipping at the far left or right edges.",
      "title": "Check the Histogram"
    }
  ]
}

{
  "steps": [
    {
      "text": "Stand with feet shoulder-width apart. Point toes slightly outward (about 15–30°). Check that your weight is evenly distributed across both feet before you begin.",
      "title": "Set Your Foot Position"
    },
    {
      "text": "Stand tall with your chest up and shoulders pulled back and down. Avoid rounding your upper back. Imagine a string pulling the top of your head toward the ceiling.",
      "title": "Stack Your Spine"
    },
    {
      "text": "Brace your core as if you're about to take a punch to the stomach. Keep this tension throughout the movement — it protects your lower back during the squat.",
      "title": "Engage Your Core"
    },
    {
      "text": "Lift both arms straight out in front of you at shoulder height. This counterbalances your body weight as you descend and helps you stay upright.",
      "title": "Extend Your Arms Forward"
    },
    {
      "text": "Push your hips back as if reaching for a chair behind you. Then bend your knees, tracking them over your toes. Do NOT let your knees cave inward.",
      "title": "Hinge Hips and Bend Knees"
    },
    {
      "text": "Lower yourself until your thighs are parallel to the floor (or as close as comfortable). Your heels should stay flat on the ground. If they lift, stop a little higher.",
      "title": "Reach the Bottom Position"
    },
    {
      "text": "Check that your chest is still up and your lower back isn't rounding. Your knees should align with your middle toe. Adjust before rising if anything feels off.",
      "title": "Verify Your Position"
    },
    {
      "text": "Press through your entire foot — heel and toes — to drive yourself back up. Squeeze your glutes as you rise. Straighten your hips and knees at the same time.",
      "title": "Drive Back to Standing"
    },
    {
      "text": "At the top, check that your hips are fully extended and glutes are squeezed. Avoid locking your knees. This is your reset point before the next rep.",
      "title": "Complete the Rep"
    },
    {
      "text": "Repeat for 5 slow, controlled reps. Focus on feeling each body part in the correct position. Quality matters more than speed — pause at the bottom on each rep if needed.",
      "title": "Practice 5 Full Reps"
    }
  ]
}

{
  "steps": [
    {
      "text": "Separe: 500g de farinha de trigo, 10g de fermento biológico seco, 10g de sal, 15g de açúcar, 300ml de água morna e 30ml de óleo. Coloque cada ingrediente em tigelas separadas antes de começar.",
      "title": "Separe os ingredientes"
    },
    {
      "text": "Despeje os 300ml de água morna em uma tigela pequena. A temperatura ideal é de 35–40°C — ao tocar, deve parecer levemente quente, não escaldante. Água muito quente mata o fermento.",
      "title": "Aqueça a água"
    },
    {
      "text": "Adicione o fermento seco e o açúcar na água morna. Mexa levemente e aguarde 10 minutos. O fermento está ativo quando a mistura formar uma camada espumosa na superfície.",
      "title": "Ative o fermento"
    },
    {
      "text": "Em uma tigela grande, despeje a farinha e faça um buraco no centro. Adicione o sal nas bordas da farinha — nunca diretamente sobre o fermento, pois o sal inativa o fermento.",
      "title": "Misture a farinha e o sal"
    },
    {
      "text": "Despeje a mistura de fermento ativado e o óleo no buraco do centro da farinha. Com um garfo ou colher, misture do centro para as bordas até a farinha estar incorporada e a massa começar a se formar.",
      "title": "Adicione o fermento à farinha"
    },
    {
      "text": "Transfira a massa para uma superfície limpa e levemente enfarinhada. Comece a sovar empurrando a massa com a base da palma da mão, dobrando e girando a cada movimento.",
      "title": "Inicie a sova da massa"
    },
    {
      "text": "Continue sovando por 10 minutos sem parar. A massa está no ponto certo quando ficar lisa, elástica e não grudar nas mãos. Se grudar, adicione farinha aos poucos — uma colher de sopa por vez.",
      "title": "Sove por 10 minutos"
    },
    {
      "text": "Faça uma bola com a massa e coloque em uma tigela levemente untada com óleo. Vire a massa uma vez para cobrir todos os lados com óleo. Isso evita que resseque durante o descanso.",
      "title": "Unte e boleie a massa"
    },
    {
      "text": "Cubra a tigela com um pano úmido ou filme plástico. Deixe descansar em local quente e sem vento por 1 hora, ou até dobrar de volume. A massa está pronta quando pressionar levemente e ela não voltar completamente.",
      "title": "Cubra e deixe descansar"
    }
  ]
}

{
  "steps": [
    {
      "text": "Ubica las llaves de paso debajo del fregadero o en el medidor principal. Gíralas en sentido horario hasta que queden completamente cerradas. Abre el grifo para confirmar que no sale agua.",
      "title": "Cierra el suministro de agua"
    },
    {
      "text": "Abre completamente el grifo para liberar el agua restante en las tuberías. Espera hasta que deje de salir agua por completo. Coloca una toalla debajo para proteger el área de trabajo.",
      "title": "Vacía el agua restante"
    },
    {
      "text": "Busca el tapón decorativo en la parte superior del mango y retíralo con un destornillador plano. Encontrarás un tornillo debajo. Quítalo con un destornillador Phillips y jala el mango hacia arriba para desmontarlo.",
      "title": "Desmonta el mango del grifo"
    },
    {
      "text": "Usa una llave ajustable para girar en sentido antihorario la tuerca de empaque que sostiene el cartucho o la válvula. Retírala con cuidado y colócala a un lado. Anota su posición antes de desmontarla.",
      "title": "Retira la tuerca de empaque"
    },
    {
      "text": "Sujeta el cartucho con unos alicates y jala hacia arriba para extraerlo. Si está muy ajustado, gíralo ligeramente mientras jalas. Llévalo a la ferretería para conseguir un repuesto idéntico.",
      "title": "Extrae el cartucho o válvula"
    },
    {
      "text": "Mientras tienes el grifo abierto, observa los aros de goma (juntas tóricas) alrededor de la válvula. Si están agrietados o deformados, retíralos con un destornillador y reemplázalos por unos del mismo tamaño.",
      "title": "Revisa y cambia las juntas tóricas"
    },
    {
      "text": "Aplica una capa delgada de grasa para fontanería sobre las juntas tóricas y el cartucho nuevo antes de instalarlo. Esto facilita el montaje y prolonga la vida útil de las piezas.",
      "title": "Lubrica las piezas nuevas"
    },
    {
      "text": "Inserta el cartucho nuevo en la misma posición que tenía el original. Empuja firmemente hasta que encaje en su lugar. Asegúrate de que las muescas de alineación coincidan correctamente.",
      "title": "Instala el cartucho nuevo"
    },
    {
      "text": "Coloca la tuerca de empaque sobre el cartucho y apriétala girando en sentido horario con la llave ajustable. No la aprietes en exceso para no dañar las roscas ni el cartucho.",
      "title": "Ajusta la tuerca de empaque"
    },
    {
      "text": "Desliza el mango sobre el vástago del cartucho y fíjalo con el tornillo que retiraste. Apriétalo bien con el destornillador Phillips y vuelve a colocar el tapón decorativo hasta que encaje.",
      "title": "Vuelve a montar el mango"
    },
    {
      "text": "Abre lentamente la llave de paso en sentido antihorario. Deja correr el agua unos segundos y observa el grifo. Si ya no gotea, la reparación fue exitosa. Si persiste la fuga, revisa que la tuerca de empaque esté bien apretada.",
      "title": "Restaura el suministro y verifica"
    }
  ]
}

{
  "steps": [
    {
      "text": "Before saving, make sure your document is open and you have typed at least some content. You should see your text on screen in the word processor window.",
      "title": "Open Your Document"
    },
    {
      "text": "Click the File menu in the top-left corner of the screen. A dropdown menu will appear with options like New, Open, Save, and Save As.",
      "title": "Open the File Menu"
    },
    {
      "text": "Click Save As from the dropdown menu. This opens the Save As dialog box, which lets you choose where to save your file and what to name it.",
      "title": "Select Save As"
    },
    {
      "text": "In the Save As dialog, look for the folder browser on the left side. Click Documents or another preferred folder to choose where your file will be stored.",
      "title": "Choose a Save Location"
    },
    {
      "text": "Click inside the File Name field at the bottom of the dialog box. It may already contain a default name like \"Document1\". Clear it by pressing Ctrl+A, then type your chosen file name.",
      "title": "Enter a File Name"
    },
    {
      "text": "Click the Save As Type dropdown (below the file name field). Select Word Document (.docx) for standard compatibility, or choose another format if required.",
      "title": "Select the File Format"
    },
    {
      "text": "Click the Save button in the bottom-right corner of the dialog. The dialog will close and your document title bar will update to show the new file name.",
      "title": "Click Save"
    },
    {
      "text": "Look at the title bar at the top of the window. It should now display your chosen file name without any asterisk (*) or unsaved indicator. This confirms your file was saved successfully.",
      "title": "Confirm the File Was Saved"
    },
    {
      "text": "Press Ctrl+S (Windows) or Cmd+S (Mac) anytime you make further changes. The document saves instantly without opening a dialog. Make this a habit to avoid losing work.",
      "title": "Save Future Changes Quickly"
    }
  ]
}

{
  "steps": [
    {
      "text": "Gather all components: CPU, RAM sticks, storage drive, GPU, PSU, motherboard, and case. Also have a Phillips-head screwdriver, anti-static wrist strap, and thermal paste ready before opening any boxes.",
      "title": "Gather components and tools"
    },
    {
      "text": "Put on your anti-static wrist strap and clip it to an unpainted metal surface. If you don't have one, periodically touch the metal case frame to discharge static electricity and protect sensitive components.",
