    },
    {
      "text": "Apply a pea-sized dot of thermal paste to the center of the CPU. Don't spread it — the cooler will do that. If your cooler has pre-applied paste, skip this step and wipe off any existing paste on the CPU first.",
      "title": "Apply thermal paste"
    },
    {
      "text": "Position the CPU cooler over the CPU, aligning its mounting holes with the motherboard standoffs. Press down evenly and secure the screws in an X pattern (diagonally opposite corners) to ensure even pressure.",
      "title": "Mount the CPU cooler"
    },
    {
      "text": "Plug the CPU cooler fan cable into the CPU_FAN header on the motherboard. It's usually a 4-pin connector located near the CPU socket. The header is labeled CPU_FAN on the board.",
      "title": "Connect the cooler fan"
    },
    {
      "text": "Locate the RAM slots — typically 4 slots on the motherboard. Check the manual for dual-channel configuration (usually slots 2 and 4). Press down the retention clips on both ends of the target slots to open them.",
      "title": "Identify the RAM slots"
    },
    {
      "text": "Align the notch on the RAM stick with the notch in the slot. Press down firmly and evenly on both ends until you hear two clicks and both retention clips snap back into place. Repeat for additional sticks.",
      "title": "Install the RAM"
    },
    {
      "text": "Remove the I/O shield from the motherboard box and snap it into the rectangular cutout at the rear of the case. Press firmly around all edges until it clicks flush. The tabs should align with the motherboard ports.",
      "title": "Install the I/O shield in the case"
    },
    {
      "text": "Lower the motherboard into the case, aligning the rear ports through the I/O shield. Line up the motherboard screw holes with the brass standoffs in the case. Check all holes are aligned before securing.",
